<doc id="1063654" wikidata="Q4579763" url="?curid=1063654" title="Rossby parameter">
<text>The Rossby parameter (or simply beta formula_1) is a number used in geophysics and meteorology which arises due to the meridional variation of the Coriolis force caused by the spherical shape of the Earth. It is important in the generation of Rossby waves. The Rossby parameter formula_1 is given by

:formula_3

where formula_4 is the Coriolis parameter, formula_5 is the latitude, formula_6 is the angular speed of the Earth&#x27;s rotation, and formula_7 is the mean radius of the Earth. Although both involve Coriolis effects, the Rossby parameter describes the &quot;variation&quot; of the effects with latitude (hence the latitudinal derivative), and should not be confused with the Rossby number.

